Thus even in this technical linguistic sphere, the main value of the psalms lies in their capacity to inspireÍ¾ the supreme example is St. Augustine, whose fumbling exposition of Psalm 4, as a novice, may have been utterly wrong, but led him on to greater things [286F].

Only on Psalm 1, written during his âethical'' period, does Erasmus draw on pagan philosophers (but in vaguer terms than in the Institutio, for example) and even in this first commentary he repeats his strictures on Aristotle as a theologian [183C], partly as a rebuke to the schoolmen, but especially as a mark of respect for the truest source of wisdom, scripture.
